<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-992-642  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 992 642.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Dec 11 1989 v15 n24 p16(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new global economic order to come of age in the '90s. (economicoutlook for the 1990s) (includes related article on possibleeconomic downturn)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Rayner, Bruce C.P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Economic growth is expected to be slow and steady during the1990s, with a possibility of a severe economic recession some timeduring the decade.andP;  Even if the global economy does grow, UScorporations will have to accept increased internationalcompetition from countries such as China, India, the USSR andEastern Europe.andP;  Protectionism may increase if the US cannotaccept its new role as follower instead of leader.andP;  Suchnationalism and protectionism could lead straight to the feareddownturn.andP;  The consensus is that if the world can avoidnationalism and protectionism, the 1990s may be one of the mostprosperous decades of the 20th century.andP;  Mexico's economy is oneof the most important to watch during the 1990s.andP;  Intense growthcould result in it being tied in with the US and Canada to createa North American free trade zone.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International TradeEconomicsForecastingUnited States.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Economic growth projected to 2000. (graph)What to expect in the 1990s. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>